Use the direct two-branch implementation below:

```ts
export function clamp(value: number, minimum: number, maximum: number): number {
  if (value < minimum) {
    return minimum;
  }

  if (value > maximum) {
    return maximum;
  }

  return value;
}
```

Representative tests:

```ts
import { clamp } from "./clamp";

describe("clamp", () => {
  it("returns the minimum when value is below range", () => {
    expect(clamp(2, 5, 10)).toBe(5);
  });

  it("returns the maximum when value is above range", () => {
    expect(clamp(12, 5, 10)).toBe(10);
  });

  it("returns the original value when already in range", () => {
    expect(clamp(7, 5, 10)).toBe(7);
  });
});
```

Review: for the stated contract, this implementation is complete and correct. It preserves `value` unchanged inside the inclusive range and clamps only the two out-of-range cases.
